39","Sweden":"Sweden","Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Sweden":"Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Sweden","Innanbäcken 3, Framibyn, Nederkalix":"Innanbäcken, Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Sweden","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jåp","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  Short form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>J-</i> (  compare  Dee   and   Kay  ), now also used as an independent given name.","2  Indian male name meaning ‘victory’ in Sanskrit."],"variants":[{"name":"Jaye","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jay  , used mainly for girls."]},{"name":"Jai","meanings":["variant of   Jay 2 ."]}]},{"name":"Jakob","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["spelling of   Jacob  , now also used in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Jacob","meanings":["Biblical name, from Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>. This was borne by perhaps the most important of all the patriarchs in the Book of Genesis. Jacob was the father of twelve sons, who gave their names to the twelve tribes of Israel. He was the son of Isaac and Rebecca and twin brother of Esau. According to the story in Genesis, he was the cunning younger twin, who persuaded his brother Esau to part with his right to his inheritance in exchange for a bowl of soup (‘a mess of pottage’). Later, he tricked his blind and dying father into blessing him in place of Esau. The derivation of the name has been much discussed. It is traditionally explained as being derived from Hebrew <i>akev</i> ‘heel’ and to have meant ‘heel grabber’, because when Jacob was born ‘his hand took hold of Esau's heel’ (Genesis 25:26). This is interpreted later in the Bible as ‘supplanter’ Esau himself remarks, ‘Is he not rightly named Jacob? for he has supplanted me these two times’ (Genesis 27:36). <i>Jacob</i> is especially common as a Jewish given name, although it also became very popular among the Puritans from the 16th century onwards, and has again been widely used since the 1990s.  Compare  James ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1357051,"age":25,"year":"1495","julianDay":2267098,"description":"Russians forces invade Sweden.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1702078,"age":25,"year":"1495","toYear":"1497","julianDay":2267098,"title":"The Russo-Swedish War","description":"While in an alliance with Grand Prince Ivan III of Moscow, King Hans of Denmark and Norway invaded Sweden and was declared King of Sweden.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russo-Swedish_War_(1495%E2%80%931497)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Swedish War","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1357052,"age":27,"year":"1497","julianDay":2267829,"description":"King Hans of Denmark and Norway attacked Sweden. King Hans declared King of Sweden.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Jåp Jakob Jakobsson was born in 1470, in Sweden. He had at least 1 son with Okänt Okänt. He died in 1520, in Innanbäcken, Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Sweden, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1470–1520":"1470–1520","1470–1545":"1470–1545","1495–1539":"1495–1539","1545":"1545","1520":"1520","1497":"1497","1495":"1495","1470":"1470","1539":"1539","Sweden":"Rootsi","Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Sweden":"Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Rootsi","Innanbäcken 3, Framibyn, Nederkalix":"Innanbäcken, Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Rootsi"},"fi":{"1470–1520":"1470–1520","1470–1545":"1470–1545","1495–1539":"1495–1539","1545":"1545","1520":"1520","1497":"1497","1495":"1495","1470":"1470","1539":"1539","Sweden":"Ruotsi","Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Sweden":"Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Ruotsi","Innanbäcken 3, Framibyn, Nederkalix":"Innanbäcken, Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Ruotsi"},"fr":{"1470–1520":"1470–1520","1470–1545":"1470–1545","1495–1539":"1495–1539","1545":"1545","1520":"1520","1497":"1497","1495":"1495","1470":"1470","1539":"1539","Sweden":"Suède","Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Sweden":"Nederkalix, Norrbotten, Suède","Innanbäcken 3, Framibyn, Nederkalix":"Innanbäcken, Nederkalix, 